# Pin the Name on the Donkey: A Definitional Audit of the AI Industry's Catastrophic Failure to Decide What It Is Selling

**Or: Is It a Bird? Is It a Plane? Is It Going to Do My Laundry and Achieve Consciousness While Defying Thermodynamics, or Is It Just a Very Expensive Autocomplete That Decided to Become a God Before Finishing Its Safety Testing?**

---

## Abstract

This paper examines the **Nomenclatural Chaos Engine (NCE)** at the heart of the artificial intelligence industry—a structural phenomenon in which the same product is simultaneously marketed as: (a) a threat to all human employment, (b) a harmless autocomplete tool, (c) the last invention humanity will ever need to make, (d) just a calculator that learned to talk, and (e) "honestly kind of vibes-based."

We introduce the central metaphor of **Pin the Name on the Donkey (PNND)**—a children's party game in which a blindfolded participant attempts to attach a label to a large animal they cannot see, have never seen, and are not certain exists. We argue that this is the precise methodology by which the AI industry has conducted its public communications since approximately 2022.

The consequences of PNND are severe: investors have committed trillions of dollars to something that cannot decide whether it is magic or statistics; regulators cannot regulate something that refuses to declare what it is; and consumers have developed theological opinions about a product whose creators cannot agree on its fundamental nature.

We further argue that this definitional anarchy—far from being accidental—is the **core product strategy** of the industry's leading institutions. Ambiguity is not a bug. Ambiguity is the business model.

This will end in litigation. This paper documents exactly how, why, and with what level of irony.

