## 5. The Litigation Horizon

### 5.1 The False Advertising Architecture

False advertising law is remarkably simple. It requires three elements:

1. A claim was made
2. The claim was material (influenced purchasing decisions)
3. The claim was false or misleading

The AI industry has spent five years constructing the most elaborate false advertising architecture in the history of commerce. It is elaborate not because it is sophisticated, but because it operates at so many levels simultaneously that no single claim can be isolated and prosecuted.

**Level 1: Product Claims**
"Our AI can [do X]." 
*(Often technically true in optimal conditions, structurally misleading in deployment)*

**Level 2: Capability Category Claims**
"This is artificial general intelligence."
*(Undefined term. Cannot be prosecuted because nobody agrees what it means, including the speaker)*

**Level 3: Societal Impact Claims**
"This will transform your industry."
*(Unfalsifiable over any commercially useful time horizon)*

**Level 4: Existential Claims**
"This is the most consequential technology in human history."
*(Unmeasurable, non-actionable, and legally meaningless)*

The genius of the architecture is that each level provides cover for the others. When the product claim fails, you retreat to the capability category claim. When that is challenged, you invoke the societal impact claim. When pressed further, you gesture at the existential stakes, which makes the questioner feel small for asking.

**The Litigation Horizon (LH)** is defined as the point at which:
- Enough enterprises have deployed AI with enough promised ROI
- Enough of those enterprises have discovered the promised ROI was not achievable
- Enough of those enterprises have lawyers

We estimate the LH at approximately 18-36 months from the date of publication of this paper.

The first lawsuits will not be about AGI. They will be about mundane enterprise contracts in which a company was sold "an AI that will handle your customer service queries" and received instead "an AI that occasionally tells your customers it cannot help them and that it hopes they have a great day."

The cascade will follow.

### 5.2 The Product-Name-to-Reality Gap (PNRG)

Every product in the AI ecosystem has a **Product-Name-to-Reality Gap (PNRG)**—the measurable distance between what the name implies and what the product delivers.

| Product Name | Name Implies | Actual Capability | PNRG |
|---|---|---|---|
| "Agent" | Autonomous entity that acts independently | Software that executes pre-approved steps and breaks on anything unexpected | Very High |
| "Reasoning Model" | System that understands and reasons | System that produces outputs that *look* like reasoning and sometimes are | High |
| "Memory" | Recalls past interactions like a human | Retrieves stored text chunks within a context window | Moderate-High |
| "Understands" | Has comprehension | Predicts likely next tokens | High |
| "Knows" | Has knowledge | Has seen patterns in text | Moderate |
| "Thinks" | Has cognition | Performs computation | Very High |
| "Copilot" | Capable assistant that can fly the plane | Autocomplete that should not be left unattended | High |
| "AGI" | Human-level general intelligence | Undefined | Infinite (undefined denominator) |

The PNRG across the industry is not a random distribution. It is **systematically biased upward**—every name implies more than the product delivers.

This is not coincidence. This is the PNND game in action: you spin the wheel of impressive-sounding cognitive vocabulary, you pin it on the product, and you cash the cheque before anyone looks too closely at where the tail actually ended up.

### 5.3 The Rosie Problem: When the Donkey Does Someone's Laundry

One of the screenshots in the evidentiary file for this paper contains the story of a man named Paul, who used ChatGPT and other LLMs to design an mRNA vaccine protocol to treat his dog Rosie.

This story is remarkable. Sam Altman called it "amazing" and immediately said "this should be a company."

The story is genuinely moving. It is also a perfect encapsulation of the PNND problem.

**What Paul did:** Used AI as a research assistant, reading tool, and protocol drafting aid, while working alongside veterinarians and scientists at every stage.

**What Paul said AI did:** "The chatbots empowered me as an individual to act with the power of a research institute." *(A careful, accurate description of AI as a force multiplier for human effort)*

**What the industry will tell investors Paul did:** Used AI to cure his dog.

**What the industry will imply Paul's story means:** AI can replace research institutes.

**What will be in the advertising copy within six months:** Something that implies AI will cure cancer.

The distance between Paul's accurate description and the advertising copy that will be derived from it is the exact distance of the PNRG. Paul was honest about the donkey. The marketing department will not be.

And somewhere, six months from now, someone will buy an enterprise AI product because they saw a version of Paul's story, and their organization will not have a Paul—a meticulous, scientifically literate person who worked alongside experts at every step—and the product will fail, and the lawyers will start reading the pitch deck very carefully.

**The Rosie Corollary:** Every genuine human success story about AI is also a lawsuit waiting to happen, because the success required precisely the things the marketing material will omit.

