## 6. The Taxonomy of Claim Types and Their Falsifiability

### 6.1 The Falsifiability Ladder

Not all claims are equal. We propose a **Falsifiability Ladder (FL)** for AI claims, ranked from most to least falsifiable:

**Rung 1 — Falsifiable (Bottom):** "Our model achieves X% accuracy on benchmark Y."
*(Can be tested. Occasionally true. Occasionally quietly corrected when not true.)*

**Rung 2 — Conditionally Falsifiable:** "Our model can do task X better than a human professional."
*(Depends heavily on which human, which conditions, and whether the task has been slightly modified to favour the model.)*

**Rung 3 — Hedged Projection:** "AI will transform industry X within Y years."
*(Technically falsifiable after Y years, by which time the speaker has redefined "transform" and moved on.)*

**Rung 4 — Career-Length Claims:** "AI will fundamentally change the nature of work in our lifetimes."
*(Our lifetimes are long. This will be neither confirmed nor denied for decades. Perfect litigation-proof zone.)*

**Rung 5 — Theological Claims (Top):** "We are building something that may be the most consequential technology in human history."
*(Completely unfalsifiable. Irrefutable. And useless as a product specification.)*

The AI industry's communications strategy involves **ascending the ladder as quickly as possible whenever a lower rung is challenged.** If Rung 1 fails (the benchmark was gamed), retreat to Rung 3 (the industry will transform anyway). If Rung 3 is challenged (it's been three years and nothing has transformed), ascend to Rung 5 (you just don't understand the historical significance of what we're doing).

This is the PNND strategy made explicit: when someone finds where you actually pinned the tail, move the donkey.

### 6.2 The Jensen Huang Theorem

On or around March 2026, Jensen Huang, CEO of Nvidia, stated: "We've achieved AGI."

This is a remarkable statement for several reasons.

First, there is no agreed definition of AGI.

Second, the entity making the claim is not an AI researcher. He is the CEO of the company that manufactures the chips on which other companies' models run—a remarkable jurisdictional extension.

Third, the statement prompted the response from "The physical physicist" account shown in the evidentiary screenshots: "Aww but I did an SOP and everything are you telling me there is no AGI I'm bitterly disappointed."

This response is funnier than anything this paper can produce, and we acknowledge it.

But it is also exactly the right response to Rung 5 claims: the correct answer to "we have achieved AGI" is not a philosophical debate. It is: "Great, where is it? I have some laundry."

**The Jensen Huang Theorem (JHT):** A claim of AGI achievement is unfalsifiable until someone hands the claimant a basket of unsorted socks.

AGI that cannot fold laundry is not general intelligence. It is a very impressive document editor.

