## 7. The Strategic Ambiguity Endgame

### 7.1 Why the Game Cannot Continue Indefinitely

Every definitional game ends the same way: reality intervenes.

The PNND strategy works for exactly as long as:

1. The claims are not tested against contractual obligations
2. The timeline for promised capabilities keeps extending without penalty
3. The investors believe future revenue will justify present losses
4. The regulators cannot agree on a definition long enough to regulate it

All four conditions are currently deteriorating simultaneously.

**Condition 1 (Contractual Testing):** Enterprise AI deployments are now large enough, and old enough, that the promised ROI is being audited. The audits are not all positive.

**Condition 2 (Timeline Extension):** GPT-5 has been "coming soon" for long enough that the joke has written itself. AGI was "5-10 years away" in 2016, 2018, 2020, 2022, and 2024. At some point, the timeline extension requires explanation.

**Condition 3 (Investor Belief):** The OpenAI restructuring to a for-profit entity, the $7 trillion infrastructure ask, and the DeepSeek efficiency revelation have collectively raised a question that VC investors do not like: *What is the actual path to profitability?* This question is structurally incompatible with the PNND strategy.

**Condition 4 (Regulatory Definition):** The EU AI Act has done something the industry dreads: it has attempted to define categories. Definitions create accountability. Accountability creates litigation risk. Litigation risk concentrates minds.

### 7.2 The Collapse Sequence

We project the following **Definitional Collapse Sequence (DCS):**

**Phase 1 — The Benchmark Reckoning:** Academic and independent researchers systematically demonstrate that the capabilities being claimed on benchmarks do not transfer to real-world deployment. (This phase is already underway.)

**Phase 2 — The Enterprise Disappointment:** Large enterprise customers who signed multi-year AI contracts in 2023-2024 publish case studies about what actually happened. A significant proportion will be negative. (This phase begins in 2025-2026.)

**Phase 3 — The Litigation Phase:** The first major lawsuits emerge, not about existential risk or copyright, but about product misrepresentation. A company was told the AI would handle X. The AI did not handle X. The pitch deck said X was handled. Discovery begins. (Estimated: 2026-2028.)

**Phase 4 — The Regulatory Crystallization:** Having watched Phase 3, regulators produce definitions. The definitions are blunt, imperfect, and politically influenced. But they exist. This ends the era of maximum definitional flexibility. (Estimated: 2027-2030.)

**Phase 5 — The Nostalgic Rebranding:** The surviving AI companies, stripped of their most extravagant claims, rebrand as "productivity tools," "decision support systems," and "intelligent automation platforms." These are honest names. They are also boring names. The stock prices reflect this. (Ongoing, forever.)

### 7.3 The Donkey, Finally Labeled

When the litigation settles and the regulations crystallise and the enterprise case studies have been published, what will AI actually be called?

Our prediction:

**AI will be called software.**

Very powerful software. Genuinely useful software. Software that does things no software has done before, in ways that are legitimately impressive.

But software. Subject to product liability. Subject to truth-in-advertising law. Subject to contractual remedies when it fails to perform as specified.

The donkey will have a name. It will be a boring name. And every San Francisco founder who spent five years insisting it was a deity will spend the next five years explaining to a jury exactly what they meant by "general" and "intelligence" and "within the next year or two."

