## 10. Conclusion: The Donkey Was Always the Point

### 10.1 The Core Finding

The AI industry's definitional crisis is not a failure of communication. It is the communication.

The game of Pin the Name on the Donkey is not a distraction from the product strategy. It is the product strategy.

An industry that can simultaneously claim:
- "It will take all your jobs" *(to make workers afraid and enterprises buy)*
- "It will empower every individual" *(to make consumers excited and buy)*
- "It's the most dangerous thing ever built" *(to make safety regulators deferential and legislators cautious)*
- "It's just software" *(to avoid product liability)*

...has discovered the most efficient marketing strategy in history: **the all-purpose claim that means something different to everyone and commits to nothing for anyone.**

The donkey is not the AI. The donkey is the market. The blindfold is the vocabulary. The tail is the next funding round.

And everybody is spinning.

### 10.2 The San Francisco Pipe Dream Addendum

This is not to say that none of it is real.

Paul and Rosie are real. The dog lived. The mRNA protocol was designed. The vet administered it. Human beings working alongside AI tools accomplished something remarkable.

That is real. That is worth building. That is worth funding.

The pipe dream is not that AI is useful. The pipe dream is the claim that this usefulness implies godhood.

The pipe dream is the extrapolation from "this helped Paul" to "this will replace research institutes" to "this will replace researchers" to "this will replace cognition itself" to "please invest $7 trillion."

The pipe dream is the assumption that because the technology is genuinely impressive, the marketing claims are therefore also genuinely true.

**The San Francisco Cathedral Error (SCE):** Confusing the fact that you have built something real with the belief that you have built something infinite.

Steam engines were real. They did not scale to replace all human movement.  
The internet was real. It did not replace all human sociality.  
AI is real. It will not replace all human cognition.

It will, however, replace some things. And it will be sued for claiming it could replace other things. And the lawsuits will settle. And then the technology will find its actual level.

And at that actual level, shorn of the theology and the eschatology and the venture-capital eschatological inflation, it will probably still be remarkable.

But it will be called software.

And the donkey will have a name.

And the name will be boring.

And everyone will pretend they knew that all along.

